 Financial statements typically show the Average Holding Period of the portfolio, that is the weighted average of the portfolio value over some specific period divided by changes of the same portfolio value over the same period. It is the sum of the portfolio value over many periods divided by the sum of the portfolio value changes over the same periods. Thus this usually means that one should not recalculate Average Holding Period of changes over period, but first to calculated it (using mathematical method), and then use this result as an inpout variable in calculation.
However, Average Holding Period varies frequently as it is based on the look period of the given bar. If you need Average Holding Period expressed in years (or quarters, months, weeks) then you would be looking at Turn-over/ Turnover ratio. Which is typically the inverse of the holding period. Turnover/ Turnover ratio could be expressed in number of periods and can be calculated in any period (in quarters, moths, quarters etc.)
## Turnover/Ratio

\begin{align}
turnover\, ratio=\frac{1}{Holding\, period\, in\, given\, periods}
\end{align}
